The '''Florence Marathon''' ({{lang-it|Maratona di Firenze}}) is an annual full-length [[marathon]] race which takes place in late November in [[Florence]], [[Italy]]. Established in 1984, the international competition has significantly grown in size since its inaugural edition of 462 runners <U+2013> it received a record 10,000 entries for the 2009 race.<ref>Sampaolo, Diego (2009-11-26). [http://www.iaaf.org/LRR09/news/newsid=54978.html Record field of 10,000 runners the new barrier for Kosgei to clear <U+2013> Florence Marathon, PREVIEW]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-11-30.</ref> It holds [[IAAF]] Label Road Race status.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/lrr09/results/index.html Road Race Label Events 2009]. [[IAAF]] (2009). Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref>

[[Orlando Pizzolato]], a two-time [[New York Marathon]] winner, was present to inaugurate the race in 1984.<ref name=Presentation>[http://212.19.106.232/B3P_FirenzeMarathon/B3L_Portal_Resources/Pubblico/Modules/Common/WF_PaginaStatica.aspx?idPaginaStatica=10&codiceSostituzione=&keySostituzione= Presentation]. Firenze Marathon (2009). Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref>  The competition's first course was about a kilometre short of the true marathon distance, and it was increased for all subsequent editions.<ref name=ARRS>Civai, Franco (2008-12-26). [http://www.arrs.net/HP_FrzMa.htm Firenze Marathon]. [[Association of Road Racing Statisticians]]. Retrieved on 2009-11-30.</ref> The current course, which was created in 2001, starts at the [[Piazzale Michelangelo]] and finishes in [[Piazza Santa Croce]]. It passes through much of Florence's historical town centre, with architecture dating from the 13th century, including: [[Piazza della Signoria]], [[Ponte Vecchio]], and the [[Basilica of Santa Croce, Florence|Basilica of Santa Croce]].<ref name=Presentation/>

The course of the race traces a winding path, initially heading west, and repeatedly zigzags back on itself as it passes many of the touristic sights of the city.<ref>[http://212.19.106.232/B3P_FirenzeMarathon/B3PortalConfig/DinamicPortalFiles/FileComuni/Percorso/PERCORSO.pdf Course plan 2009]. Firenze Marathon (2009). Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref> This makes it a particularly difficult marathon as runners have to contend with the course's many bends, as well as cobblestone roads.<ref>Sampaolo, Diego (2008-11-30). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=48460.html Kenya and hosts share honours in Florence Marathon]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref> The race begins by gently going uphill, continues with a downhill section between the 2<U+2013>5&nbsp;km marks, and features a largely flat course from this point until the finish.<Ref>[http://212.19.106.232/B3P_FirenzeMarathon/B3L_Portal_Resources/Pubblico/Modules/Common/WF_PaginaStatica.aspx?idPaginaStatica=111&codiceSostituzione=&keySostituzione= The Course of XXVI Firenze Marathon]. Firenze Marathon (2009). Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref> An [[Association of International Marathons and Distance Races|AIMS]]-certified course,<ref>[http://www.aimsworldrunning.org/Directory.htm#ITA AIMS Race Directory]. [[Association of International Marathons and Distance Races|AIMS]] (2009). Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref> it has an overall net drop of 75&nbsp;m thus it is ineligible for [[List of world records in athletics|world records]].<ref name=ARRS/>

Italians form the bulk of the runners, while [[France]], [[Germany]] and the [[United Kingdom]] are usually the next most represented nationalities in the field.<ref>[http://212.19.106.232/B3P_FirenzeMarathon/B3L_Portal_Resources/Pubblico/Modules/Common/WF_PaginaStatica.aspx?idPaginaStatica=211&codiceSostituzione=&keySostituzione= Statistics 2008]. Firenze Marathon (2008). Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref> From 2005 to 2009, the competition was annually broadcast live for three hours on the state-owned [[Rai Tre]] channel.<ref name=Presentation/> The race is among Italy's most prominent <U+2013> it was selected to be the national championship marathon race for the first time in 2003.<ref name=ARRS/> The current course record holders are [[James Kutto]], who set the men's record of 2:08:41 in 2006, and [[Helena Javornik]] ran 2:28:15 in 2002 to set the women's record.<ref>[http://212.19.106.232/B3P_FirenzeMarathon/B3L_Portal_Resources/Pubblico/Modules/Common/WF_PaginaStatica.aspx?idPaginaStatica=174&codiceSostituzione=&keySostituzione= Albo D'Oro] {{it icon}}. Firenze Marathon. Retrieved on 2009-12-02.</ref>

